{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement--> | official_name = Etimesgut | settlement_type = District | image_skyline = Guzelkent19.JPG | image_caption = Eryaman neighborhood in Etimesgut | image_blank_emblem = | blank_emblem_type = | image_map = Ankara districts.png | map_caption = Location of Etimesgut within Turkey. | pushpin_map = Turkey | coordinates = {{coord|39|57|N|32|40|E|region:TR|display=inline}} | subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]] | subdivision_name = {{TUR}} | subdivision_type1 = [[Regions of Turkey|Region]] | subdivision_name1 = Central Anatolia | subdivision_type2 = [[Provinces of Turkey|Province]] | subdivision_name2 = Ankara | leader_title = [[Governor]] | leader_name = Recep Erkılıç | leader_title1 = [[Mayor]] | leader_name1 = Enver Demirel ([[Nationalist Movement Party|MHP]]) | area_footnotes = {{Turkey district areas|SOURCE}} | area_blank1_title = District | area_blank1_km2 = {{Turkey district areas|Ankara|Etimesgut}} | elevation_m = 807 | population_footnotes = {{Turkey district populations|SOURCE|Ankara}} | population_as_of = {{Turkey district populations|YEAR}} | population_urban = {{Turkey district populations|Ankara|Etimesgut|şehir}} | population_blank1_title = District | population_blank1 = {{Turkey district populations|Ankara|Etimesgut|toplam}} | population_density_blank1_km2 = auto | timezone = [[Eastern European Time|EET]] | utc_offset = +2 | timezone_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]] | utc_offset_DST = +3 | postal_code_type = [[Postal code]] | postal_code = 06xxx | area_code = 0312 | blank_name = [[Turkish car number plates|Licence&nbsp;plate]] | blank_info = 06 | website = [http://www.etimesgut.gov.tr/ www.etimesgut.gov.tr] }}
'''Etimesgut''' or '''Etimesut''', formerly '''Ahimesut''', is a metropolitan district of [[Ankara Province]] in the [[Central Anatolia Region, Turkey|Central Anatolia]] region of [[Turkey]], mainly consisting of large public housing projects, {{convert|25|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from [[Ankara]] city centre. According to 2010 census, population of Etimesgut is 386,879 .<ref>[http://report.tuik.gov.tr/reports/rwservlet?adnksdb2=&ENVID=adnksdb2Env&report=idari_yapi_09sonrasi.RDF&p_il1=6&p_yil=2010&p_dil=2&desformat=html]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Statistical Institute</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geohive.com/cntry/turkey.aspx?levels=Ic%20Anadolu|title=Statistical information on Turkey's administrative units|accessdate=2008-03-29|author=GeoHive}}</ref> The district covers an area of {{convert|49|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=on}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statoids.com/ytr.html|title=Statistical information on districts of Turkey|accessdate=2008-05-01|author=Statoids}}</ref> and the average elevation is {{convert|807|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}.
== Demographics ==
{{Historical populations |title = Historical population<ref>Turkish Statistical Institute</ref> |align = none |cols = 1 |shading = off |percentages = pagr |2007|289601 |2008|313770 |2009|347267 |2010|386879 |2011|414739 |2012|425947 |2013|469626 |2014|501351 |2015|527959 |2016|542752 }}
==History== Archaeological research shows habitation since 2000 BC, including a [[Phrygia]]n settlement in the 8th century BC. Then of course the district began to share the history of the city of Ankara with its [[Lydians]], [[Persia]]ns, [[Galatia]]ns, [[Ancient Romans]], [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]] and finally [[Turkish peoples|Turks]]. Etimesgut is on the ancient [[Silk Road]] to the orient, and still today the road and railway from Ankara to [[Istanbul]] pass through the district.
[[Atatürk]] was fond of the area and would come here to ride horses and chat to the locals. He had a room in the building that is the public health laboratory today, and many other public buildings, including the hospital and the post office, that were built by his order still stand today.
Etimesgut began as a housing project of 50 homes ordered by Atatürk in 1924 to accommodate [[Turks in Bulgaria|Turkish]] refugees from [[Bulgaria]]. From the 1950s, as poverty forced people to migrate from the countryside into the city much illegal housing [[gecekondu]] was thrown up in this district. Some of this has been replaced by public housing projects such as Elvankent, [[Eryaman, Etimesgut|Eryaman]] and [[Güzelkent, Etimesgut|Güzelkent]] and also military and civil service accommodation. However much ''gecekondu'' remains, inhabited by working-class people from cities such as [[Erzurum]], many of whom commute to jobs in the city of Ankara. The Islamic terrorist organisation [[Hizbullah (Turkey)|Hizbullah]] had a number of hidden cells here in the 1990s.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}
==Present== The area has only the most basic shops and amenities. Almost all of the housing in Etimesgut is apartment buildings except for the Güzelkent project. As building land in the city of Ankara is now impossible to find, areas like this on the fringes of the city, where building land is cheap, are growing faster and faster.
Public buildings include the sugar factory, the Turkish aviation authority headquarters at Etimesgut Airport and a military training camp.
The local football team [[Etimesgut Şekerspor]] has a chequered history; in recent years it has gained popularity by hiring former national team player [[Sergen Yalçın]].
==Planned security campus== The construction of a new building in Etimesgut is underway, to serve as the joint new headquarters of the Turkish [[National Intelligence Organization (Turkey)|National Intelligence Organization]] (MİT), the [[Ministry of National Defence (Turkey)|Ministry of National Defence]], and the [[Turkish General Staff]] together with the commands of the Army, Navy and Air Force branches of the [[Turkish Armed Forces]]. Reportedly, the move, which will turn the area into a "security campus" comparable to the [[US Pentagon]], is part of measures taken after the failed [[2016 Turkish coup d'état attempt]]. <ref>{{cite news |title=MİT, MSB ve komutanlıklar Etimesgut'ta toplanacak |author=Deniz Çiçek |url=http://www.haberturk.com/gundem/haber/1305407-mit-msb-ve-komutanliklar-etimesgutta-toplanacak |newspaper=[[Haberturk]] |date=4 October 2016 |accessdate=5 October 2016 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Turkish Pentagon' to be formed in capital Ankara: Report |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-pentagon-to-be-formed-in-capital-ankara-report.aspx?PageID=238&NID=104570&NewsCatID=338 |newspaper=[[Hürriyet Daily News]] |date=4 October 2016 |accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref>
==Neighborhoods== {{columns-list|colwidth=22em| * [[Alsancak, Etimesgut|Alsancak]] * [[Altay, Etimesgut|Altay]] * [[Atakent, Etimesgut|Atakent]] * [[Ayyıldız, Etimesgut|Ayyıldız]] * [[Bağlıca, Etimesgut|Bağlıca]] * [[Bahçekapı, Etimesgut|Bahçekapı]] * [[Elvan, Etimesgut|Elvan]] * [[Elvankent, Etimesgut|Elvankent]] * [[Erler, Etimesgut|Erler]] * [[Etiler, Etimesgut|Etiler]] * [[Eryaman, Etimesgut|Eryaman]] * [[Güzelkent, Etimesgut|Güzelkent]] * [[İstasyon, Etimesgut|İstasyon]] * [[Kazım Karabekir, Etimesgut|Kazım Karabekir]] * [[Oğuzlar, Etimesgut|Oğuzlar]] * [[Piyade, Etimesgut|Piyade]] * [[Süvari, Etimesgut|Süvari]] * [[Şehit Osman Avcı, Etimesgut|Şehit Osman Avcı]] * [[Şeyh Şamil, Etimesgut|Şeyh Şamil]] * [[30 Ağustos, Etimesgut|30 Ağustos]] * [[Topçu, Etimesgut|Topçu]] * [[Tunahan, Etimesgut|Tunahan]] * [[Şeker, Etimesgut|Şeker]] * [[Yapracık, Etimesgut|Yapracık]] * [[Yavuz Selim, Etimesgut|Yavuz Selim]] * [[Yeşilova, Etimesgut|Yeşilova]] }}
==Former broadcasting site== At Etimesgut, there was a longwave broadcasting station with two masts each 256 metres tall, which worked on 198&nbsp;kHz. The station, whose masts stood at {{coord|39|56|24.07|N|32|40|3.2|E|type:landmark|name=Etimesgut transmitter, mast north}} and at {{coord|39|56|14.33|N|32|40|3.03|E|type:landmark|name=Etimesgut transmitter, mast south}} was built in 1938 and shut-down in 2004 and was afterwards demolished.
