The '''Parliamentary Elections Act 1770''' (also known as the '''Grenville Act''') is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of Great Britain]] (10 Geo III c. 16). The Act transferred the power of trying [[election petition]]s from the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] to the [[Judiciary of England and Wales|Judiciary]]. All contested elections were to be considered by a committee of thirteen members selected by ballot. The Act was initially limited to one year, but was extended several times. A bill was passed in 1774 to make it perpetual — by that time five cases had already been tried.
This Act was repealed by section 1 of the Controverted Elections Act 1828 (9 Geo. IV c. 22).
==References== *Erskine May, Chapter VI, pp.&nbsp;362–75, ''Election Petitions: Places and Pensions''{{year missing|date=February 2013}}[http://www.ra.smixx.de/emay1v362.pdf]
